roblems anticipated modern abstraction","body":"Vanderpoel's 1902 'Color Problems' translated color theory into hundred-square grids sampling everything from mummy cases to butterfly wings. Long overlooked, the book is now read as anticipating Klee, Albers, and Rothko by decades.","number":2},{"category":"social_reform","header":"She remade Litchfield in Colonial Revival","body":"As curator of the Litchfield Historical Society, Vanderpoel drove the town's Colonial Revival, behind the restorations of the Congregational Church and the Litchfield Law School. She also helped found the local DAR chapter named for her great-grandmother Mary Floyd Tallmadge.","number":3},{"category":"legacy","header":"She finished her son's gift to Litchfield","body":"When her son John Arent died with his library building unfinished, Emily completed the project and set a memorial tablet to him beneath its Palladian window. The building honored her mother, Julia Tallmadge Noyes.","number":4}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[{"artwork_id":"ART082","role":"creator"}],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"X03136","display_label":"her father-in-law, Congressman Aaron Vanderpoel"},{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"HD3004","display_label":"led Hartford's preservation as Vanderpoel did Litchfield's"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Emily Caroline","last_name":"Noyes","display_name":"Emily Caroline Noyes Vanderpoel","gender":"female","married_names":["Vanderpoel"],"maiden_name":"Noyes","bio_blurb":"Artist and author of \"Chronicles of a Pioneer School\"","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780940427/Photo_of_Emily_Noyes_Vanderpoel_excifx.jpg"},"military_service":[],"career":[],"birth":{"year":1842,"country":"United States","city":"New York","state":"New York"},"death":{"year":1939,"country":"United States","city":"New York","state":"New York"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM749"},"education":[],"slug":"emily-caroline-noyes-1842"},"X03136":{"id":"X03136","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"male","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"is_easter_egg":true},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["politics","law"],"notable_blurb":"U.S. Congressman; the 'Kinderhook Roarer'","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aaron_Vanderpoel","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"parents":{},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X03137","children_ids":["I01627"],"marriage_number":1}],"tags":["congressman","judge","lawyer"],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"politics","header":"The 'Kinderhook Roarer' of Congress","body":"A Jacksonian and later Democratic congressman from New York, Vanderpoel served three terms between 1833 and 1841. His booming voice and oratory earned him the nickname the 'Kinderhook Roarer.'","number":1},{"category":"law","header":"A friend of Van Buren on the bench","body":"A close friend of President Martin Van Buren, Vanderpoel practiced law in Kinderhook before entering Congress. He later sat as a judge of the New York Superior Court from 1842 to 1850.","number":2}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"HD6027","display_label":"father-in-law of this Hooker descendant"},{"type":"artifact","related_id":"T01819","display_label":"recorded this family in his New York and New England genealogy"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Aaron","last_name":"Vanderpoel","display_name":"Aaron Vanderpoel","gender":"male","bio_blurb":"U.S. Congressman, the 'Kinderhook Roarer'","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780941581/6897661_1036123583_pjow7x.jpg"},"military_service":[],"career":